<br />
   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Strategy:<br />
<br />
First of all, mad props to primalfire for posting Throne Bone EBO.  I was deeply impressed by it, and immediately began to ponder a way to make my own version of it.  I’ve played TRM for quite awhile now, and was (and still am) convinced that it is probably the best or 2nd best light side deck out there right now if played well.  At the same time, I’ve been thinking about making EBOX swarm with Hidden Base.  When I built HB EBO however, I found that it put too many cards on the table and it just took too long to set up.  When I combined EBOX with TRM, this is what I found:<br />
<br />
Going first is a HUGE advantage for LS.  It’s like getting an extra turn to do whatever you want.  This let’s EBO get up very quickly very consistently.  Plus, TRM is so strong because of the force denial and insane activation starting around turn 2 or so.  Plus X-wings are so fun to mess with your opponent.  Anyway, on to the strat:<br />
<br />
First Turn:<br />
<br />
Pull DDTA first if you see Mob Points.  Pull your generals, activate, pull Echo Docking Bay.  Plop Riekann down, get 1st and 4th markers.  If you have an echo site, some cheap character, or maybe a signal in your hand, congrats, you’ll get EBO up even faster.  That should be about it.<br />
<br />
Second turn:<br />
<br />
Riekann pulls A New Secret Base which gets your other sites, or a site and EBO.  Now just occupy the 3 sites and put it out.  Navander (v) pulls systems, and you’re ready to rock.  The insanity now begins.<br />
<br />
Rest of game:<br />
<br />
Riekann gets out the Forest, where your epps can go and have immunity to all attrition (huge).  They can also go play with your opponent if you want to knock their characters off of battlegrounds.  Rebel Fleet cancels drains, spread with the xwings and have your lovely interrupts ready to party.  Is there a nasty Executor you don’t like?  Power pivot it with some xwings and let HCF add even more insult to injury.  They have no power plus maybe two destinies and you have at least 20 power plus two destinies.  It’s fun!  The most evil starfighter for DS, ZiMH, bows before x-cannons.  Between Houjix, Barrier, Alternatives, Organized Attack, and Power Pivot, you should have no trouble spreading out at the systems to drain.  Spreading is key to maximize EBO damage.  Warning:  Secret tech about to follow.<br />
<br />
Card choices:<br />
<br />
Ralltiir:  Why ralltiir?  What’s so special about that dumb system?  This is the secret tech.  It won’t always work, but if it does you can really rock your opponent.  Just leave one lone xwing there, and spread the rest out.  When your opponent rushes you, BAM, all starfighters within range can react there.  Then you just power pivot/organized attack/out of nowhere/whatever them into oblivion.  Granted intelligent DS players might read the system’s text, but c’mon, I’ll bet a lot of people won’t.<br />
<br />
Insight/Honor:  These might get cut soon.  I’d don’t like decks like Huntdown, Deal, Watto, Walkers etc that deal direct damage.  Honor can kill the damage a lot of the time, but not if you see No Escape.  You might be able to take these out.  If Walkers wasn’t so big, I would probably take it out, read Walkers matchup.<br />
<br />
Corran:  Um, why not Corran?  He’s a spy, which is sweet, he’s basically an anti-Visage machine.  When you got a Houjix ready, go send Corran after Visage.  Visage damage is REALLY annoying, and w/o it, HD damage is just drains from Vader vs. drains from crazy Ebo xwing drains.<br />
<br />
MATCHUPS:<br />
<br />
Walkers:  I figure I better put this matchup first since the entire SWCCG world has gone walker crazy right now.  Believe it or not, I don’t think this matchup is impossible at all.  Before you flame me and tell me that “Walkers own you! lol” consider the following.  Riekann comes down and pulls est. secret base first turn.  EBO can easily come down 2nd turn.  Goo may slow them down a bit, plus, after they blow the generator Garrison is useless.  Menace Fades kills Garrison as long as I control a hoth location.  I plan on controlling a bunch of echo sites.  Plus, No Escape doesn’t stop honor from reducing drains at nonbattlegrounds.  Either way, garrison shouldn’t do a darn thing against you.  Definitely start Menace Fades.  Atrocity (v) knocks the 8 damage down to 6, then reduces the YMSYL damage.  I might put in even more atrocities to reduce it further, plus to be ready for the controls.  Time AWRI for when you can retrieve the atrocities.  <br />
<br />
This leaves the big blue space problem.  If they run star destroyers, barrier/power pivot/organized attack/you know the rest to knock them out.  If they run bounty hunter ships, shoot ‘em down.  If you’re still worried about Walkers, I’d put in Kessel to help the drains.  All in all, just keep the drains going, and keep minimizing their damage while knocking them out of space.  It won’t be an easy matchup, but it’s definitely winnable even if it will be close.<br />
<br />
Hunt Down:  Try to get Corran to cancel Visage.  Be ready to Houjix him, or use Weapons Display to get him out of there.  Honor will help if they can’t get their No Escape.  The bottom line is that their damage potential is crap w/o visage.  They’re limited to drains and beatdowns.  The drains shouldn’t be bad at all, and some folks at the Forest should be able to hold their own.  You shouldn’t have a problem at all controlling space.<br />
<br />
Deal:  Definitely start Menace Fades.  If it’s Speed Deal, there’s not much you can do to stop them from doing their thing.  You can definitely fight them for the sector or system, but be careful with the interrupts.  Some of them only work at systems.  Basically keep Menace Fades working and let EBO take it to them.  I would stay away from CC sites unless you really think you have an opportunity to hurt them.  Overrall I think you have the advantage here.  <br />
<br />
SYCFA:  Yuck, not a very fun deck to play against most of the time.  Again this is a good reason why I want to put in another Atrocity (v).  You and your opponent are big blue, so this shouldn’t be a boring matchup.  Don’t forget that Fear requires them to control the system for you to lose the damage.  There’s nothing wrong with spreading out, avoiding battles, then coming back with HCF, weapons, and fun interrupts.  Plus, they’ll probably give you more systems to play at.  This matchup should be fun and i think it is very winnable.  Be VERY wary of going to their docking bay, there’s no way you can hurt them there, but a well-placed Put All Sections on Alert can hurt you big time.  I think you have the advantage here, but I’d have to play the matchup to know for sure.<br />
<br />
CCT:  This v6 wonder is all the rage now too.  They take your Han, too bad he’s not a staple of your space package.  If the opportunity arises for you to clear the popsicle’s site, go for it i guess, but you don’t need HCF.  I’m almost tempted to not suspend mob pts to give them the free Executor.  Power pivot is that much fun  :)  Seriously tho, DDTA really slows down their damage.  By the time they get the big Executor out, you should be ready for it.  If they come at you with BH ships, shoot em down, it’s not too hard.  Menace Fades might cancel the Despair (v) bonus, I’m not sure.  I think we’re still waiting for Greg to make an official ruling about it.  Either way, one drain isn’t enough to seriously hurt you.  Rule the skies and you should be fine.<br />
<br />
Watto:  Hmmm, it’s a good thing you go first.  Speed Watto is a real pain to play against, but when LS goes first, it can be fun.  Suspend their Mob pts to delay the big Executor coming down for free.  I’d start Insight just to force them to start No Escape.  If they don’t start No Escape for some reason, congrats on your victory!  Watto +  Honor working =  LS autowin.  I’d let them deploy whatever they want most of the time.  You don’t really care about Tatooine, and their space probably won’t be too bad.  Of course, if you have a great chance to attack on Tatooine take it, but don’t expect to get one.  If they run Occupation, go cancel it.  EBO should be too much for them.<br />
<br />
What else.......<br />
<br />
BHBM:  This could actually be a bit nasty.  I don’t like to give up Luke, and I really don’t like getting him converted for an auto-loss.  If you can get Honor to work, go for it.  Choose your battles wisely, you don’t want to have to stack anything.  Look for chances to take out Vader, but I think EBO damage should really hurt him too much.  BHBM generally runs like one BG to satisfy Your Destiny.  Goo will also hurt him, his generation probably isn’t very high.<br />
<br />
Combat:  Thank them for giving you all the force!  Again this decktype doesn’t run too much space usually.  The difference is that combat can cause LOTS of ground damage.  Start Menace Fades, and get EBO going as fast as possible.  One nifty trick I like to do is put quiggy at the naboo site next to maul, then some other guy at maul’s site.  Maul can’t battle you or do the finger of death.  Maul has to move over, generally giving you a place to drain.  You’ll probably take early damage here, AWRI is a big help.  <br />
<br />
Well, I think that’s about it.  I don’t think I missed any major decktypes...lemme know if I did and I’ll edit them in.<br />
<br />
Cards I want in here:<br />
<br />
Incom Corporation (I know it’s huge, i just don’t know what to take out)<br />
Another Atrocity<br />
Civil Disorder non v<br />
Boussh<br />
Life Debt<br />
Legendary Starfighter<br />
<br />
I might as well put in a quick word about Decree (v).  I’ve been playing TRM for quite awhile now, and I really don’t see Decree as a big deal.  I don’t generally put out all my icons at once, so by the time i have them out, they should be relying on their own activation.  I don’t mind them losing a force at the start of their turn tho, if they want to.  Also, I’d say this deck is maybe 20% offensive, 80% defensive.  You aren’t really going after your opponent’s characters and stuff unless it’s cake.  The strength of this deck is spreading thin in space and letting EBO put the pressure on.  This forces your opponent to come after you, which is where your interrupts go wild.  <br />
<br />
Please leave constructive feedback (lemme know what to take out for what’s coming in).  It’s a fun deck to play and can be pretty strong too.<br />
<br />
May the greatest CCG game ever created never die.<br />
<br />
Aglets<br />
